Webmaster / Analytics / Ads Services Setup

1. General Explanation

Webmaster, analytics, and ads services are like special helpers for your website. They let you see how people find your site, what they do when they visit, and how you can share ads or messages with them.

2. What We Do

We set up and connect tools like Google Search Console (Webmaster), Google Analytics (tracking visitors), and ad platforms (like Google Ads) so your website can collect valuable information. This includes verifying your site with search engines, adding special codes to your site, and making sure everything is working correctly.

3. Why We Do It

By setting these services up, we can find out how many people come to your site, how long they stay, and which pages interest them. This helps us improve the site’s performance, plan better advertising strategies, and make your website easier to find in search results.

Search Console / Create resource if no resource

1. General Explanation

Google Search Console is a free tool from Google that helps us understand how your website appears in Google search results. It shows important information about things like how many people visit your site from Google, which pages are popular, and if there are any problems that might prevent people from finding you.

2. What We Do

If you don’t have a Google Search Console account, we create one for you. Then we add your website so we can see and track all the information Google collects about it. This setup also lets us fix any technical issues that might come up.

3. Why We Do It

By using Google Search Console, we make sure your website can be easily found and is free of errors. It also helps us spot any issues quickly—like broken pages or security warnings—so we can fix them. Ultimately, this helps people have a better experience on your site and improves your visibility in Google’s search results.

Search Console / Add code to website

1. General Explanation

Google’s Search Console is like a special backstage pass to your website. It helps you see how Google looks at your site and tells you if anything needs fixing so people can find you more easily on Google.

2. What We Do

We add a small piece of code (or verify your site in another way) that lets Google know, “Hey, this is our website.” Once Google confirms we’re legit, we can use Search Console to track how well your site shows up in search results and fix any issues.

3. Why We Do It

By connecting your site to Search Console, we can check if Google sees any problems, learn how many people are visiting from Google searches, and make changes to help your site do better online. That means more people can find your business when they search.

Search Console / Send home page for indexing

1. General Explanation

We use a tool called Google Search Console to let Google know your website is ready to be shown in search results. One of the most important pages we ask Google to look at is your home page.

2. What We Do

We log into Google Search Console, where we enter your home page address and tell Google to “check” or “crawl” this page. This is like raising your hand in class to let the teacher know you have the homework ready.

3. Why We Do It

Requesting Google to index your page helps ensure that it shows up in search results faster and more accurately. This way, people searching for what you offer have a better chance of finding your website.

Search Console / Add sitemaps

1. General Explanation

Think of a sitemap like a map you give to Google. It shows where the different “rooms” (pages) of your website are, so Google doesn’t get lost. Search Console is a tool that helps you talk to Google about your website.

2. What We Do

We create or update your sitemap, which is basically a list of all the pages on your website. Then we add your website and the sitemap to Google Search Console. This way, Google knows exactly where everything on your site is located.

3. Why We Do It

By giving Google this roadmap, your website pages are found faster, which can help them show up more in search results. Plus, Search Console lets us see if there are any problems with your website that stop Google from finding or showing your pages.

Search Console / Check Manual Actions & Security Issues

1. General Explanation

Google Search Console is like a report card for your website. It tells you if Google sees any problems—such as breaking its rules or having security dangers—so you can fix them and keep your site running smoothly.

2. What We Do

We look inside your Search Console account to see if there are any “manual actions,” which are basically warnings or penalties from Google. We also check for any security alerts, like hacked pages or harmful code. If we find issues, we figure out how to fix them and make things right with Google.

3. Why We Do It

We do this so your website keeps showing up in Google’s search results. If Google thinks your site breaks the rules or is unsafe, it might push your site down in the search listings or even hide it completely. By checking and fixing these problems right away, we make sure visitors can find your site and feel safe using it.

Analytics / Create account, rescource, data stream

1. General Explanation

This step is all about setting up a tool (like Google Analytics) that tells us how people use your website. It’s like putting a friendly observer on your site who takes notes on how many people visit, which pages they look at, and how long they stay.

2. What We Do

  • We create an analytics account (think of it as your own special dashboard)
  • We set up a “resource” (basically, setting up the part of the tool that focuses on your website)
  • We connect a “data stream” (this is how your website sends information—like when someone visits—to the analytics system)

3. Why We Do It

  • To get clear information on how people interact with your website (for example, which pages are most popular)
  • To help you make decisions on what to improve, based on real visitor data
  • To measure the results of any changes or updates and see if they’re making your website better for visitors

Analytics / Set 14 months in “Admin – Data retention – Data retention”

1. General Explanation

Google Analytics helps us understand how people use your website by gathering visitor information. Data retention is the length of time Google Analytics keeps this information.

2. What We Do

In the Google Analytics “Admin” area, we set the “Data Retention” period to 14 months. That means Google Analytics will only store past data for 14 months before it’s automatically deleted.

3. Why We Do It

By choosing 14 months, we have enough history to see patterns and trends, but we also make sure we aren’t hanging on to outdated visitor information too long. This helps protect people’s privacy while still giving us useful insights about how the site is used.

Analytics / Add pre-defined key events (see description)

1. General Explanation

We want to make sure we’re tracking important actions on your website—like when someone clicks a “Buy Now” button or fills out a form. These actions are called “key events.” By setting up these events, we can tell exactly what people do on your site.

2. What We Do

We add special codes to your website that record each time a visitor does something important, like starting a chat, playing a video, or making a purchase. These codes send that information to your analytics tool, which collects and organizes it.

3. Why We Do It

Tracking these key events helps us understand how visitors use your site—what grabs their attention and what might be confusing. This way, we can decide what to improve or change, so more people have a great experience and do what you want them to do (like buying a product or signing up for a newsletter).

Analytics / Connect to GSC and GAds

1. General Explanation

Connecting a website to tools like Google Analytics (GA), Google Search Console (GSC), and Google Ads (GAds) lets us see how people find and use the site. Google Analytics tracks visitor behavior, Google Search Console shows how the site appears in Google search results, and Google Ads handles advertising information.

2. What We Do

We place small pieces of code (or “tags”) on the website and make sure these tools (GA, GSC, and GAds) are properly linked to your site. This might include setting up accounts, verifying ownership, and adjusting settings so everything collects information accurately.

3. Why We Do It

By connecting the website to these tools, we can see how well it’s performing, learn which pages people visit the most, and find out if our advertising is helping us reach the right audience. This helps us make better decisions about improving the website and using our marketing budget wisely.

Tag Manager / Create account, container

1. GENERAL EXPLANATION

A Tag Manager is like a toolbox for your website. It helps you easily add and keep track of different “tags”—little pieces of code you place on your site for things like analytics and tracking. Instead of opening your website’s code every time you need to add or change a tag, you can do it in one place—your Tag Manager.

2. WHAT WE DO

We create a Tag Manager account and set up a “container.” Think of the container like an envelope that holds all your tags. By creating this account and container, we give ourselves a safe spot to manage the special codes we want to add to your site, so we don’t have to touch your site’s code directly every single time.

3. WHY WE DO IT

We do this to keep things organized and make updates faster. The Tag Manager lets us add or change tags without needing to manually edit every page of your site. This helps us track important site data (like visits and clicks) and gather the information we need to make your website work better—and it’s all done in one secure place.

Tag Manager / Add Tag Manager to website

1) General Explanation:

A Tag Manager is like a special container for all the little “trackers” or “tags” on your website (for example, Google Analytics, Facebook tracking, etc.). Instead of placing each tag’s code separately all over your website, the Tag Manager holds them all in one place and controls when and where they show up.

2) What We Do:

We set up or add a Tag Manager tool (often Google Tag Manager) to your website. This means we add one small piece of code onto your site. Then, from the Tag Manager’s dashboard, we can easily add or remove different tags, adjust settings, or organize your tracking code without having to go back into the website’s main code.

3) Why We Do It:

  • It keeps your website tidier by gathering all your tracking codes in one place.
  • It makes it much simpler (and faster) to update, add, or remove tags.
  • It lowers the chance of mistakes when managing many different bits of code.

Tag Manager / Connect GA 4

1. General Explanation

Tag Manager (such as Google Tag Manager) is a tool that helps us manage and place various tracking codes on a website without needing to change the website’s code each time. Google Analytics 4 (GA4) is a newer version of Google’s tool that shows how people use a website.

2. What We Do

  • We set up or check that Google Tag Manager is connected to the website.
  • We make sure GA4 is correctly linked through Tag Manager, so the website’s visitor data is recorded.

3. Why We Do It

  • Tag Manager saves time and reduces mistakes because we don’t have to change the website code for every new tracking script.
  • Connecting GA4 helps us see how people find and use the website, allowing us to make better decisions to improve the site.

Tag Manager / Setup form submission / purchase tracking

1. General Explanation

A Tag Manager is like a helper that collects information about what people do on your website. It’s especially useful for tracking important actions, like when someone fills out a contact form or buys something.

2. What We Do

  • We set up a Tag Manager on your site (this is a tool that holds little bits of code).
  • We make sure every time a form is filled out or a purchase is made, the Tag Manager captures this event.
  • We test these “events” to confirm they’re being recorded correctly.

3. Why We Do It

  • This helps us see how many people complete forms or buy products on your site.
  • Knowing what works and what doesn’t lets us improve your website and marketing.
  • It’s a way to measure success so we can keep making things better for your visitors and your business.

Tag Manager / Setup phone click tracking

1. General Explanation

Tag Manager is like a central control center for all the little “trackers” on your website. One important tracker is phone click tracking, which helps us see if people are clicking your phone number to call you.

2. What We Do

We install and set up the Tag Manager on your website so we can see how many visitors tap your phone number. This involves adding small bits of code (tags) that let us record each time someone clicks the phone number link.

3. Why We Do It

Knowing how many people are clicking to call helps us understand how well your website is working. If lots of people call after visiting, it tells us that they’re interested in your business and that your website is helping them reach you.

Tag Manager / Setup mail click tracking

1. General Explanation

A tag manager is like a conductor for all the tracking tools on your website. It helps us keep everything in one place and makes sure each tool knows what to do. One of these tools tracks when someone clicks on an email link (like “Contact Us here!”). That way, we can see how many people are trying to contact you through email directly from your site.

2. What We Do

We set up the tag manager to listen for clicks on email links. Whenever a visitor clicks a link that opens an email to you, the tag manager notes it. This information is sent to a tracking system (like Google Analytics), so we can count how many people are connecting with you that way.

3. Why We Do It

Tracking email link clicks tells us how many visitors want more personal contact or have questions for you. This helps us understand which pages or offers encourage people to reach out. With those insights, we can make better decisions about where to improve your website and how to better serve your visitors’ needs.

Bing Webmaster / Add website (import from GSC)

1) General Explanation:

Bing Webmaster Tools is like a helper that makes sure your website shows up and looks good in the Bing search engine. Just as Google Search Console (GSC) helps with Google, Bing Webmaster Tools helps with Bing.

2) What We Do:

We sign in to Bing Webmaster Tools and add your website to the system. To make this faster and easier, we use the information you already have in Google Search Console and import the website details directly from there.

By telling Bing about your website in this official way, we ensure that Bing can find and understand your site. This increases the chances of your website appearing in Bing search results, which helps more people discover your business online.

Google Alerts / Set alerts for grey/black niches words

1) General Explanation

Google Alerts is a free tool from Google that lets us receive email updates when certain words or phrases are mentioned on the internet. When we talk about “grey/black niche” words, we mean words related to risky or spammy topics that could hurt our website’s reputation if our site is associated with them.

2) What We Do

We create special Google Alerts for these suspicious or risky words. This way, we can quickly see if anyone is mentioning our website alongside these words or if these words are suddenly popping up in connection with our brand.

3) Why We Do It

By keeping an eye on these alerts, we protect our website and brand. If something bad or questionable is said about us or if our site is linked to harmful topics, we can act fast to address any issues, clear up misunderstandings, and maintain a positive online reputation.

Technical analysis

1. General Explanation

Technical analysis is like giving your website a “health check-up” to make sure everything behind the scenes is working smoothly. Just like you want your computer to run without glitches, you also want your website to run fast, be easy to view on any device, and use the right coding tools.

2. What We Do

  • We test how quickly your website loads and fix anything slowing it down.
  • We make sure it works well on phones, tablets, and computers.
  • We look at the coding (HTML, CSS, JavaScript) for any mistakes that might cause errors or slowdowns.
  • We check the server (the “home” of your website) to ensure it’s configured correctly.

3. Why We Do It

  • A faster, smoother website makes visitors happy and keeps them from leaving in frustration.
  • Ensuring it looks good on all devices helps more people use your site comfortably.
  • Correct coding helps avoid errors that could break parts of the website.
  • Having a well-set-up server can keep your site secure and prevent downtime.

Domain normalize / Check for redirection (http://, http://wwww, https://www, https)

1. General Explanation

Sometimes websites can be accessed in different ways, like with or without “www,” or with “http” instead of “https.” Domain normalization means making sure all these different web addresses send everyone to just one main address.

2. What We Do

We check if your website sends visitors from any version of the address (like http://yourwebsite.com or http://www.yourwebsite.com) to the same place (usually the https://www.yourwebsite.com version). If it doesn’t, we set up or fix the “redirects” so all traffic goes safely to one address.

3. Why We Do It

Having just one main address for your website avoids confusion, makes the site look more trustworthy, and helps search engines rank you better. It also improves security by making sure people always land on the secure (https) version of your site.

Domain normalize / Check for redirection with Uppercase letters in domain

1. General Explanation

Sometimes, when people type your website address, they might use uppercase letters instead of lowercase (for example, EXAMPLE.com instead of example.com). Even though it looks almost the same, using uppercase letters can confuse search engines and some browsers. We want to make sure your domain (website address) always looks and works the same way no matter how people type it.

2. What We Do

We check if your website correctly directs visitors when uppercase letters are used. If someone goes to EXAMPLE.com (all uppercase) or ExAmPlE.com (mixed letters), we make sure they are sent to the same version of your site—usually the all-lowercase version. If it’s not set up correctly, we add or fix a redirect so that every visitor ends up on your preferred, consistent domain.

3. Why We Do It

Making your domain consistent helps search engines see it as just one website instead of multiple versions. This makes your site easier to find, rank, and trust. It also avoids confusion for your visitors, ensuring they always end up at the correct place, no matter how they type your web address.

Domain normalize / Check for redirection with several “//” in slug

1. General Explanation

Sometimes a website can appear to have more than one address or have messy links (like two slashes in a row, “//”) that lead to the same page. This can confuse search engines and visitors. By making sure the site always uses the same domain name (for example, always “example.com” instead of “www.example.com”) and by avoiding “//” in the links, we keep things neat and organized.

2. What We Do

We look at the website’s addresses (URLs) to confirm they all go to the same place. If they don’t, we set up rules so that any incorrect or messy URL automatically sends people (and search engines) to the correct, tidy address. We also make sure there aren’t extra “//” that might cause broken links or unnecessary redirects.

3. Why We Do It

Having a single, consistent domain name and clean links helps search engines recognize and trust your website. It also makes it easier for visitors to find and share your site without running into confusing or broken links. This all leads to a smoother user experience and better search engine performance.

Sitemap / Should be valid

1. General Explanation

A sitemap is like a map that shows search engines (like Google) all the important pages on your website. It helps them find and understand your site’s pages more easily.

2. What We Do

We check if the sitemap is properly set up and can be read by search engines without any errors. We make sure it includes all important pages and follows the right format so that nothing is missing or broken.

3. Why We Do It

When the sitemap is valid, it helps search engines quickly discover and list (or “index”) your website pages. This can improve the way your site is shown in search results, making it easier for people to find you.

Sitemap / Shouldn’t contain trash, demo, no-content pages

1. General Explanation

Think of a sitemap like a table of contents for your website. It lists all the pages so that visitors and search engines can quickly find what they’re looking for. If the sitemap is filled with pages that are not real, are duplicates, or have no useful content, it can be confusing and unhelpful.

2. What We Do

We review your sitemap and remove any “junk” pages, demo pages, or pages with no real information. This way, your sitemap only leads to pages that provide real value.

3. Why We Do It

By cleaning up the sitemap, we make sure search engines (like Google) easily understand and rank the pages that matter. This helps your website appear more trustworthy and improves its overall performance in search results.

Sitemap / Shouldn’t contain pages with 3xx, 4xx, 5xx response codes

1. General Explanation

Imagine a sitemap as a list of your website’s pages, like a table of contents for a book. When this list includes pages that don’t work properly (showing error messages or redirecting oddly), it can confuse both visitors and search engines.

2. What We Do

We make sure that none of the pages in your sitemap return 3xx (redirect), 4xx (not found or bad request), or 5xx (server error) response codes. Essentially, we remove any broken or problematic links from your sitemap.

3. Why We Do It

By keeping only healthy pages in your sitemap, we help search engines find and understand your site better. This can improve your website’s visibility and overall user experience since search engines and visitors won’t waste time on pages that don’t work.

Sitemap / Shouldn’t contain pages with get-parameters

1. General Explanation

Your sitemap is like a list of your website’s most important pages that helps search engines (like Google) find and understand your content. Pages with “GET-parameters”—those little bits after a question mark in a URL, like “?id=123”—can confuse search engines and make your sitemap messy.

2. What We Do

We review the sitemap to make sure it only includes the clean, main versions of each page. If we see any pages with extra “?something=anything,” we either remove them from the sitemap or convert them to their proper link.

3. Why We Do It

This keeps your sitemap clear and organized, so search engines don’t get tripped up by weird links or duplicate pages. A clean sitemap means better online visibility and a smoother experience for everyone.

Sitemap / Shouldn’t contain directives noindex / nofollow (X-Robots)

1. General Explanation

A sitemap is a special file or page on your website that guides search engines (like Google) to all of the important pages you want people to find. It’s like a roadmap that shows how everything is connected.

2. What We Do

We look inside the sitemap to check if there are any instructions that say “noindex” or “nofollow” (these are sometimes called X-Robots directives). If we find them, we remove them or fix them. These instructions tell search engines to ignore certain pages, which doesn’t make sense in a sitemap—because the whole point of a sitemap is to help search engines find and show your pages.

3. Why We Do It

We do this to make sure search engines can properly see and list all the pages you actually want people to find. If “noindex” or “nofollow” instructions are left in the sitemap, it can prevent search engines from showing those pages in search results, which might cause you to miss out on website visitors.

Sitemap / Shouldn’t contain links where canonical != page

1. General Explanation

A sitemap is like a map of all the important pages on your website, and your “canonical tag” tells search engines which version of a page is the “official” one. If a page in the sitemap points to a different URL than the page says is official, it can confuse both users and search engines about which page is the correct one.

2. What We Do

We check each link in your sitemap to make sure it doesn’t point to a page that has a different “official” URL set by its canonical tag.

3. Why We Do It

When sitemaps include links that don’t match their official (canonical) pages, search engines might ignore or index the wrong pages, leading to lower visibility in search results and a worse experience for visitors. Ensuring the sitemap matches the canonical URLs helps keep your site organized and clear for both people and search engines.

Robots.txt / Shouldn’t have “disallow” for important pages

1. General Explanation

The robots.txt file is like a set of instructions for search engines, telling them which pages of your site they can or cannot visit. If a page is marked “disallow,” it means search engines are told not to look at that page.

2. What We Do

We check your robots.txt file to make sure no important pages are being blocked by a “disallow” rule. If any page that matters to your site is mistakenly disallowed, we will correct it.

3. Why We Do It

We do this because we want search engines to be able to access and show these important pages in their results. If the pages are blocked, they won’t appear in search results, and people won’t be able to find them as easily.

Robots.txt / Shouldn’t have “disallow” for pages with noindex / nofollow

1. General Explanation

Robots.txt is a small file on your website that tells search engines which pages they can or cannot visit. It’s like a “do not enter” sign for certain pages. However, if a page is set to “noindex” or “nofollow,” you usually want search engines to visit it first so they can see these instructions—telling them the page shouldn’t be shown in search results or shouldn’t pass its links to other pages.

2. What We Do

We look at your robots.txt file to make sure it does not block (Disallow) the pages that are already labeled as “noindex” or “nofollow.” If we find such pages are blocked here, we fix it by removing that blocking line so search engines can actually see the noindex/nofollow tags on the page itself.

3. Why We Do It

If these pages are blocked in robots.txt, search engines won’t even look at them, and won’t realize that they shouldn’t be shown or followed. Correcting this allows search engines to read the page and apply the noindex or nofollow instructions properly. This helps keep your website’s search appearances under control and avoids confusion for search engines.

Robots.txt / Should have “sitemap” directive with valid link to sitemap

1. General explanation

The robots.txt file is like an “instructions book” for search engines when they visit your website. It can tell them which pages to look at and which pages to skip. Including a “sitemap” directive in this file gives search engines a direct link to your sitemap, which is a list of all the main pages on your website.

2. What we do

We check your robots.txt file to see if it includes a line that points to your sitemap. If it’s missing or incorrect, we add or fix it so that your sitemap link is valid and easy for search engines to find.

3. Why we do it

We want search engines to quickly find and understand the structure of your website. By including the “sitemap” directive, we make sure they know exactly where to look. This helps more of your pages get listed in search results, making it easier for people to discover your site.

Robots.txt / Should have “disallow” for AI crawlers

1. General Explanation

The robots.txt file is like a set of rules you place at the front door of your website. It tells different “visitors” (search engines and some AI crawlers) which parts of the site they can or cannot enter. Think of it like a sign on your house saying “please do not enter” certain rooms.

2. What We Do

We add specific instructions in the robots.txt file saying “Disallow” to AI crawlers. This tells them, “Hey, you’re not allowed to come in and collect data from these areas of our site.” It’s like having a polite, but firm, “no trespassing” sign.

3. Why We Do It

We do this to protect sensitive or private website content, keep AI tools from automatically collecting everything on our site, and ensure that only the pages we want to share openly are accessible. In other words, it helps us keep some control over who is looking at our information.

Canonicals / Check for canonicals with 3xx, 4xx, 5xx response codes

1. General Explanation

“Canonical” tags are like telling search engines, “Hey, this is the main version of this page!” If the link in the canonical tag sends visitors or search engines to a broken page (4xx or 5xx) or causes too many jumps (3xx), it confuses the search engines about which page is really the main one.

2. What We Do

We check all the canonical tags on your website to see if they lead to pages with normal (200) responses. If any canonical tag points to a page with a 3xx redirect or an error (4xx or 5xx), we note it so it can be fixed.

3. Why We Do It

When a canonical tag points to the wrong place—or leads to errors—search engines may not show the correct main version of your page in search results. Fixing these issues helps keep your site organized and makes it easier for visitors to find the right information.

Canonicals / Check for canonicals pointing to noindex pages

1. General Explanation

A “canonical” is like a sign telling search engines which page is the “main” or “preferred” version of some content on your website. A “noindex” page is one that tells search engines not to list it in search results. If a page has a canonical that points to a noindex page, it’s basically pointing to a page that’s hiding from search engines—this can create confusion for Google and other search engines.

2. What We Do

We check every page on your website to make sure that if it has a canonical link, it does not point to a page that’s labeled “noindex.” If we find any pages with this mistake, we update the canonicals so they point to the correct “main” page that should be featured in search results.

3. Why We Do It

If a canonical points to a noindex page, search engines can get mixed signals: one part of your site is saying, “This is the main page,” and another part is saying, “Don’t show it!” By fixing these issues, we make sure search engines understand which pages to show in their results, improving your site’s visibility and overall performance.

Canonicals / Check for canonicals pointing to page disallowed with robots.txt

1. General Explanation

A canonical link is a small piece of code that tells search engines which version of a webpage should be treated as the “main” one. This prevents confusion when there are multiple pages with very similar content. However, if the “main” page is blocked from being crawled by robots.txt (which tells search engines where they can and cannot look), that can cause problems.

2. What We Do

We carefully check whether any of the canonical links on your website point to pages that are blocked by robots.txt. If we find canonical links pointing to blocked pages, we’ll fix them so they point to pages search engines are actually allowed to see.

3. Why We Do It

If a canonical link points to a page that search engines are not allowed to visit, it can create confusion about which page is really the “main” one. By making sure the canonical links point to accessible pages, it helps search engines understand your website better and ensures your pages can appear properly in search results.

Canonicals / Check for canonicals of pages with get-param point to page without get-param

1. General Explanation

On websites, sometimes we have the same page but with extra information in the web address (like “?id=123”). A canonical tag tells search engines which version of the page is the “main” or “official” one. This helps avoid confusion if there are different versions of the same page.

2. What We Do

We check to make sure that if a page has a special link with extra details (like “?id=123”), the canonical tag is pointing back to the normal version of the page (the one without those extra details).

3. Why We Do It

By telling search engines which page is the main one, we prevent them from splitting attention between many slightly different links. This boosts our chances of ranking well because there’s only one recognized “primary” version of the page.

Canonicals / Pagination pages canonical should be self-canonical

1. General Explanation

When you have multiple versions of the same or very similar web pages (like page 2, page 3, etc.), each page should tell search engines, “I am my own main version.” We do this by using something called a “canonical tag.” If Page 2 accidentally points to Page 1 as the main version, search engines can get confused and skip showing Page 2 in search results.

2. What We Do

We check all your paginated pages—like those “Next” and “Previous” pages—and make sure each one has a canonical tag that points to itself. This confirms to search engines that Page 2 is actually Page 2, and Page 3 is actually Page 3.

3. Why We Do It

When each page correctly identifies itself, search engines won’t mix them up or think they’re duplicates. This helps all your web pages appear in search results the way you want, so you don’t lose any important traffic or visibility.

3xx, 4xx, 5xx / Check for internal links with 3xx, 4xx, 5xx response codes

1. General Explanation

These numbers (3xx, 4xx, 5xx) tell us how a webpage reacts when we try to visit it:

  • 3xx means the page is redirecting us somewhere else (like a change of address).
  • 4xx means the page can’t be found or we’re not allowed to see it.
  • 5xx means there’s a problem with the website’s server.

2. What We Do

We check all the links within your website to see if any of them lead to these special codes. If any link does, it means the link either redirects people unexpectedly (3xx), leads to a missing page or error (4xx), or isn’t working at all because of a server problem (5xx).

3. Why We Do It

Finding and fixing these errors helps make sure your website is easy and pleasant to use. If someone clicks a link and gets an error or unexpected redirection, they might get frustrated and leave. Also, search engines prefer websites without broken or confusing links, so fixing these issues can help your website appear more reliable and trustworthy online.

3xx, 4xx, 5xx / Check for external links with 3xx, 4xx, 5xx response codes

1. General Explanation

When you browse the internet, every time you load a page or click on a link, the website server sends back a status code―a short message that tells your browser what’s going on. For example, “3xx” often means the page you asked for has moved somewhere else, “4xx” usually means there’s something wrong with the link request (like a missing page), and “5xx” means the website’s server is having problems.

2. What We Do

We look at all the external links (links that send you to other websites) on your site and check if any of them are returning these 3xx, 4xx, or 5xx codes. For instance, some links might be redirecting (3xx) or may no longer work (4xx or 5xx). We collect this information so we can see which links need attention.

3. Why We Do It

We want to make sure your website visitors don’t run into issues like clicking on a link and finding it broken or redirected to a strange place. By checking these status codes, we can fix or update links to give everyone a smoother, more reliable experience on your website.

3xx, 4xx, 5xx / Check for 3xx redirect chains and loops

1. General Explanation

When you visit a website, different codes let us know what’s happening behind the scenes. For example, 3xx codes mean the page is trying to send you somewhere else (a redirect). A 4xx code happens when something goes wrong on your side or the link doesn’t exist (like a broken link). A 5xx code means the website’s server made a mistake and couldn’t show the page.

2. What We Do

We look closely at these codes to see if the site has any problems. Specifically with 3xx codes, we check for redirect chains and loops. A redirect chain happens when one page sends you to another page, which sends you to another, and so on. A loop is even worse because it sends you in a circle, so you never reach a final page.

3. Why We Do It

Too many redirects, broken links, and error pages can frustrate visitors and make the website feel poorly maintained. By finding and fixing these problems, we keep your website fast, user-friendly, and easy for search engines to understand—so more people can find and enjoy your site.

Content / Check for cannibalizaton via Looker Studio

1. General Explanation

Sometimes, websites have more than one page talking about the same topic. When this happens, those pages can “fight” with each other to show up in search results—this is called “cannibalization.” It can confuse both search engines and people looking for your information.

2. What We Do

We use a tool called Looker Studio (previously known as Google Data Studio) to spot and compare pages targeting the same keywords. We look at the data—like which pages are ranking for certain search terms—and see if multiple pages from your site overlap too much.

3. Why We Do It

By checking for cannibalization, we can figure out if certain pages should be combined or made more unique. This helps your site perform better, because search engines and visitors can clearly tell which page has the best answer for a topic without confusion.

Schema / Set schema.org template for Home, About Us, Blog, Service + Product, Person

2) What We Do

We place the correct schema “tags” on important pages—such as your Home page, About Us page, Blog, Service or Product pages, and any Person profiles. These tags help describe the page content (like who you are, what service you offer, and where you’re located).

3) Why We Do It

This helps search engines show your pages in more useful ways, like adding extra details (star ratings, images, pricing) on the search results page. That often means people find your site more easily and are likelier to visit, which can lead to more business.

Cluster keywords

2. What We Do

First, we collect all the terms people might use when they search for your website’s topics. Then, we organize these words into groups based on how they’re related. That way, each group focuses on one main idea.

Divide semcore into service and blog pages

1. General Explanation

“Semcore” (short for “semantic core”) is simply the group of words and phrases that best describe what your website is about. It’s helpful to think of it like a dictionary of all the topics and keywords important to your business. We divide these keywords into two main categories: the services pages (where you directly talk about your offerings) and the blog pages (where you share articles, tips, and other information).

2. What We Do

We look at all the keywords that relate to your business and sort them based on where they make the most sense—service pages or blog pages. For example, words that people use when they’re ready to buy or learn about services go on service pages. Words for explaining ideas and sharing helpful information go on blog pages.

3. Why We Do It

When search engines see a clear distinction between service pages and blog pages, they can better match your pages to the right search queries. This helps potential customers find exactly what they need more quickly, whether they’re looking for your product or service (services pages) or just wanting to learn more about your topic (blog pages). It also keeps your website organized and easy to navigate for visitors.
